05199nam a22006855i 9780231543118DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315431187 a10.7312/seve179442doi  a(DE-B1597)478182  a(OCoLC)979588111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS3573.A425635bZ864 2019 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813.542231 aSevers, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDavid Foster Wallace's Balancing Books :bFictions of Value /cJeffrey Severs. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tNote on the Texts -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: A LIVING TRANSACTION: VALUE, GROUND, AND BALANCING BOOKS -- t1. COME TO WORK: CAPITALIST FANTASIES AND THE QUEST FOR BALANCE IN THE BROOM OF THE SYSTEM -- t2. NEW DEALS: (THE) DEPRESSION AND DEVALUATION IN THE EARLY STORIES -- t3. DEI GRATIA : WORK ETHIC, GRACE, AND GIVING IN INFINITE JEST -- t4. OTHER MATH: HUMAN COSTS, FRACTIONAL SELVES, AND NEOLIBERAL CRISIS IN BRIEF INTERVIEWS WITH HIDEOUS MEN -- t5. HIS CAPITAL FLUSH: DESPAIRING OVER WORK AND VALUE IN OBLIVION -- t6. E PLURIBUS UNUM : RITUAL, CURRENCY, AND THE EMBODIED VALUES OF THE PALE KING -- tCONCLUSION: IN LINE FOR THE CASH REGISTER WITH WALLACE -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat do we value? Why do we value it? And in a neoliberal age, can morality ever displace money as the primary means of defining value? These are the questions that drove David Foster Wallace, a writer widely credited with changing the face of contemporary fiction and moving it beyond an emotionless postmodern irony. Jeffrey Severs argues in David Foster Wallace's Balancing Books that Wallace was also deeply engaged with the social, political, and economic issues of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. A rebellious economic thinker, Wallace satirized the deforming effects of money, questioned the logic of the monetary system, and saw the world through the lens of value's many hidden and untapped meanings. In original readings of all of Wallace's fiction, from The Broom of the System and Infinite Jest to his story collections and The Pale King, Severs reveals Wallace to be a thoroughly political writer whose works provide an often surreal history of financial crises and economic policies.As Severs demonstrates, the concept of value occupied the intersection of Wallace's major interests: economics, work, metaphysics, mathematics, and morality. Severs ranges from the Great Depression and the New Deal to the realms of finance, insurance, and taxation to detail Wallace's quest for balance and grace in a world of excess and entropy. Wallace showed characters struggling to place two feet on the ground and restlessly sought to "balance the books" of a chaotic culture. Explaining why Wallace's work has galvanized a new phase in contemporary global literature, Severs draws connections to key Wallace forerunners Don DeLillo, Thomas Pynchon, and William Gaddis, as well as his successors—including Dave Eggers, Teddy Wayne, Jonathan Lethem, and Zadie Smith—interpreting Wallace's legacy in terms of finance, the gift, and office life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z978311